Congress read this letter on 22 Mar. (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:225).</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0337" class="document">Council of War, this date</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>For the march of the army to New York, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0337&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0337-fn-0002#GEWN-03-03-02-0337-fn-0002" class="document">Council of War, this date, n.2</a>. Gen. John Sullivan did not command the riflemen on their march. On 23 Mar. he was given command of a marching brigade of six regiments that departed on 29 Mar. (see the <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0414" class="document">General Orders for 23, 28 Mar. 1776</a>).</p>

</div>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0465">[465]</span>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0345" class="document">GW to Jonathan Trumbull, Sr., and GW to Lord Stirling, both 14 Mar. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>For the fortification of Nooks Hill on the night of 16 Mar., see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0363" class="document">GW to Hancock and GW to Joseph Reed, both 19 Mar. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>The letter-book copy and the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr> include here the words on the route.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>The <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr> reads &amp; forwarding such necessaries, as cannot be carried Immediately, (if proper to be carried at all) that some directions might be received from Congress, as to the number which they may judge necessary to be kept here for these or any other purposes. This portion of the letter-book copy is illegible for the most part.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0007">7</a>
	
   <p>On 14 May 1776 Congress resolved that the five batallions, now in Massachusetts bay, be recruited to their full complements, and that three additional batallions be raised in the eastern department, for the service of the continent (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:355, 360; see also <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-04-02-0244" class="document">Samuel Adams to GW, 15 May</a>, and the <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-04-02-0252" class="document">Massachusetts Delegates to GW, 16 May 1776</a>). For the five regiments left in Massachusetts, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0337&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0337-fn-0004#GEWN-03-03-02-0337-fn-0004" class="document">Council of War, this date, n.4</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0008">8</a>

   <p>The <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr> reads (there being no Major, Magaw the late one being appointed Lt Col: of one of the Pennsylvania Battalions &amp; gone from hence). This portion of the letter is missing in the letter-book copy.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0009-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0009">9</a>

   <p>On 7 Mar. Congress promoted Edward Hand to colonel of the 1st Continental Regiment and made James Chambers its lieutenant colonel (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:188; see also <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0329" class="document">Hancock to GW, 11 Mar. 1776</a>). Hugh Stephenson was promoted to colonel on 27 June 1776 when Congress resolved to form a new rifle regiment by adding six companies to the three companies of Virginia and Maryland riflemen that Stephenson then commanded (ibid., 5:486). Stephenson died sometime later this summer apparently while recruiting his regiment in Virginia (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-06-02-0324" class="document">GW to Hancock, 28 Sept. 1776</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-06-02-0371" class="document">GW to Samuel Washington, 5 Oct. 1776</a>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Historical Society of Pennsylvania, Philadelphia ]">PHi</span>: Gratz Collection). Robert Magaw (d. 1790) of Carlisle became colonel of the 5th Pennsylvania Regiment on 3 Jan. 1776 and was captured with his regiment at Fort Washington in November 1776.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0010-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0338-fn-0010">10</a>

   <p>Congress authorized the payment of this sum to William Barrell on 28 Mar. 1776 (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:238).</p>

</div>
